This is the sample data csv file.
sample.csv
we need to pass the file name and location as cmd line argument.
Run Tabe in pycharm >> Edit connfiguration >> Script parameter Copy

First we need to config Spark Config and do the


[SPARK_APP_CONFIGS] - spark.app.name = Hello Spark - spark.master = local[3] Copy
this is the property file where spark env config will be configured
lib.utils class i am creating spark config for get_spark_app_config


import configparser from pyspark import SparkConfig() def get_spark_app_config(): spark_conf = SparkConfig() config = config.ConfigParser().read("spark.conf") for key,value in config.items("SPARK_APP_CONFIGS"): spark_conf.set(key,value) return spark_conf RunCopy
Configuring the sparkconf for further use in read
import sys import os from pyspark import SparkConf from pyspark.sql import SparkSession from lib.logger import Log4J from lib.utils import get_spark_app_config if __name__ == "__main__": conf = get_spark_app_config() spark = SparkSession.builder \ .config(conf=conf) \ .getOrCreate() logger = Log4J(spark) if len(sys.argy) != 2: logger.error("Usage: HelloSpark <filename>") sys.exit(-1) logger.info("Starting Spark Session") conf_out = spark.SparkContext.getConf() logger.info("Finished HelloSpark") # ---- Read The Dataframe ---- spark_df = spark.read \ .option('header','true') \ .csv(sys.argv[1]) spark.stop() RunCopy
Here we are reading a csv file and this is complex and flexible
till here we are reading the data dataframe and with header is true as we have first rows in csv file is header
now we need to check for DataFrame DataType

So for defining data frame data type we need to use inferSchema
spark_df = spark.read \ .option('header','true') \ .option('inferSchema', 'true') \ .csv (sys.argv[1]) RunCopy
Here it will do intelligent guess for datatype and put a suitable datatype.
to view the dataframe we need to use
spark_df.show() RunCopy
![[ED-202406171359.excalidraw|1000]] Copy



After this Spark Session will start the executors
as we configured the CPU, Memory, Executors are
Configured to the spark session.
work as Driver allocation and as well providing resources like
- Cluster manager
- Resource Manager
- Container Manager

Here Spark will try to minimize the network bandwidth for loading data from HDFS to the JVM Memory.
This is Spark internal Optimizer while assigning the partition to these executor
Spark will Try its best -- Spark and Cluster Manager work together
achieve the best possible localization.

groupBy(county.count())

import sys import os from pyspark import SparkConf from pyspark.sql import SparkSession from lib.logger import Log4J from lib.utils import get_spark_app_config if __name__ == "__main__": conf = get_spark_app_config() spark = SparkSession.builder \ .config(conf=conf) \ .getOrCreate() logger = Log4J(spark) if len(sys.argy) != 2: logger.error("Usage: HelloSpark <filename>") sys.exit(-1) logger.info("Starting Spark Session") conf_out = spark.SparkContext.getConf() logger.info("Finished HelloSpark") # ---- Read The Dataframe ---- spark_df = spark.read \ .option('header','true') \ .csv(sys.argv[1]) spark.stop() RunCopy

spark_df.where("Age <40") \ .select("Age", "Gender", "Country","state") \ .groupBy("Country") RunCopy

item.title: Spark_log4jconfig
item.description:
#Creating
#Creating Spark Session
class Log4J : def __init__(self,spark): log4j = spark._jvm.org.apache.log4j self.logger = log4j.LogManager.getLogger("ankit.new_session.spark.examples") def warn(self, message): self.logger.warn(message) def info(self, message): self.logger.info(message) def error(self,message): self.logger.error(message) def debug(self,message): self.logger.debug(message) RunCopy
we can do the suffix it with application name also into it.
class Log4J : def __init__(self,spark): log4j = spark._jvm.org.apache.log4j self.logger = log4j.LogManager.getLogger("ankit.new_session.spark.examples"+"."+ "HelloSpark") def warn(self, message): self.logger.warn(message) def info(self, message): self.logger.info(message) def error(self,message): self.logger.error(message) def debug(self,message): self.logger.debug(message) RunCopy
here log4j configuration work as long as the base name matches.
We don't want to hard code like this so make it generic.
class Log4J : def __init__(self,spark): log4j = spark._jvm.org.apache.log4j conf = spark.sparkContext.getConf() app_name = conf.get("spark.app.name") self.logger = log4j.LogManager.getLogger("ankit.new_session.spark.examples"+"."+ app_name) def warn(self, message): self.logger.warn(message) def info(self, message): self.logger.info(message) def error(self,message): self.logger.error(message) def debug(self,message): self.logger.debug(message) RunCopy
After this we can define the logger now.
from pyspark.sql import SparkSession from lib_logger import Log4J if __name__ == "__main__": spark = SparkSession.builder \ .appName("SparkFirst") \ .master("local[3]") \ .getOrCreate() logger = Log4J(spark) logger.info("Starting hello") logger.info("finishing hello") spark.stop() RunCopy

item.title: Spark_Session_Configuration
item.description:
Apache Spark is highly configurable system,
Spark allows you to set those configuration using four different methods.
Configuration Spark Session : - Environment Variable - SPAR_HOME\conf\spark_defaults.conf - spark_submit command-line - SparkConf object Copy


SPAR_HOME\conf\spark_defaults.conf


SparkConf object
spark_submit command-line options

SparkConf -- is for coding configuration in application it self
spark = SparkSession.builder \ .appName("SparkConf") \ .master("local[3]") \ .getOrCreate() RunCopy
appName and Master is the SparkConf. We can config as we need as much we want.
but we should be aware for actual name.
from pyspark.sql import SparkSession from pyspark import SparkConf if __name__ == '__main__': conf = SparkConf() conf.set('spark.app.name','SparkConf') conf.set('spark.master','local[3]') RunCopy

from pyspark.sql import SparkSession from pyspark import SparkConf if __name__ == "__main__": conf = SparkConf() conf.set('spark.app.name','SparkConf') conf.set('spark.master','local[3]') spark = SparkSession.builder \ .config(conf=conf) \ .getOrCreate() spark.stop() RunCopy

SparkSessionCollection

Environment < Spark-default.cnf < CLI option < SparkConf
--->>> precedence >>> ----
Spark properties -- can be grouped in to categories


Spark Submit -- ``` ~ go to spark-submit help specially name flags such as --master --driver-memory --num-executor etc. will be used by Spark-Submit ``` Other all are `Spark Conf` object
Let say we have
conf = SparkConf() conf.set('spark.app.name','SparkConf') conf.set('spark.master','local[3]') RunCopy
we are not confirm for this are we using YARN cluster or kubernative.
If we encounter with issue we need to check in local so converting spark.master will be in application lever cause issue.
This all thing is hard coded so which isnt production based.


We can make this config to Properties file.
[SPARK_APP_CONFIGS] - spark.app.name = Hello Spark - spark.master = local[3] Copy
Created key value pair in spark.conf file
After that creating utils.py class
import configparser from pyspark import SparkConfig() def get_spark_app_config(): spark_conf = SparkConfig() config = config.ConfigParser().read("spark.conf") for key,value in config.items("SPARK_APP_CONFIGS"): spark_conf.set(key,value) return spark_conf RunCopy
once it created then call this method in main class Spark_Main.py.
import os from pyspark.sql import SparkSession from lib.logger import Log4J from lib.utils import get_spark_app_config if __name__ == '__main__': log4j_config_file = 'log4j.properties' os.environ["log4j.configurationFile"]= "file:" + log4j_config_file conf = get_spark_app_config() spark = SparkSession.builder \ .config(conf=conf) .getOrCreate() logger = Log4J(spark) logger.info("Starting HelloSpark") spark.stop() RunCopy
conf = get_spark_app_config() RunCopy
here we fixed the hard coding issue. for log4j code Spark_log4jconfig
for reading all spark config spark.config -- SparkSession.sparkContext.getConf() method
